            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the golden ratio?</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>golden ratio</strong>, usually written as
                <strong>phi</strong> (φ), is an irrational number that appears
                in geometry, art, architecture, and design. Its value is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1 text-sm"><strong>Exact value:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \varphi = \frac{1 + \sqrt{5}}{2} \approx 1.6180339887\ldots
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                A line is divided in the golden ratio when the
                <strong>whole length</strong> divided by the
                <strong>longer part</strong> is equal to the
                <strong>longer part</strong> divided by the
                <strong>shorter part</strong>.
              </p>

              <h2>Golden ratio formulas</h2>
              <h3>1. Definition using a line segment</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose a line of total length \(L\) is split into a longer part
                \(a\) and a shorter part \(b\), with \(a &gt; b &gt; 0\). The
                golden ratio condition is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \frac{a + b}{a} = \frac{a}{b} = \varphi \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>From this, we can derive the classic quadratic equation:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \varphi = 1 + \frac{1}{\varphi} \quad\Rightarrow\quad
                  \varphi^2 - \varphi - 1 = 0 \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Split a length into golden sections</h3>
              <p>Given the total length \(L = a + b\):</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ a = \frac{\varphi}{1 + \varphi} \, L \approx 0.618\,L \]
                </p>
                <p>\[ b = \frac{1}{1 + \varphi} \, L \approx 0.382\,L \]</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Our calculator uses these formulas to compute the longer and
                shorter segments for any length you enter.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Golden rectangle</h3>
              <p>
                A <strong>golden rectangle</strong> has side lengths in the
                ratio \(\varphi : 1\). If you know one side, the other is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="mb-1"><strong>Given height \(h\):</strong></p>
                <p>\[ \text{width} = \varphi \, h \]</p>
                <p class="mt-3 mb-1"><strong>Given width \(w\):</strong></p>
                <p>\[ \text{height} = \frac{w}{\varphi} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use this golden ratio calculator</h2>
              <h3>1) Split a length (for grids, margins, and spacing)</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter the <strong>total length</strong> (e.g., 1200 px, 30 cm,
                  8 in).
                </li>
                <li>Optionally type a unit label (px, cm, in, etc.).</li>
                <li>Click <strong>“Calculate golden split”</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  The tool returns:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      the <strong>longer segment</strong> (≈ 61.8% of the total)
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      the <strong>shorter segment</strong> (≈ 38.2% of the
                      total)
                    </li>
                    <li>the ratio \(a : b\) compared to φ</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Use this for column widths, sidebar vs. content, or spacing
                between elements.
              </p>

              <h3>2) Golden rectangle (for layouts and cropping)</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Choose whether you know the <strong>width</strong> or
                  <strong>height</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>Enter the value and unit (e.g., 1080 px height).</li>
                <li>Click <strong>“Calculate rectangle”</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  The calculator outputs the matching side and the exact aspect
                  ratio.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                This is useful for designing artboards, posters, slides, or
                cropping photos to a golden rectangle.
              </p>

              <h3>3) Check a ratio (how “golden” is it?)</h3>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter two positive values \(a\) and \(b\) (with \(a\) intended
                  as the larger).
                </li>
                <li>Click <strong>“Check golden-ness”</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  The tool computes:
                  <ul>
                    <li>\(a / b\)</li>
                    <li>the <strong>percentage difference</strong> from φ</li>
                    <li>a simple verdict (very close / close / not close)</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                This is handy to test existing designs, photo crops, or
                real-world measurements against the golden ratio.
              </p>

              <h2>Examples</h2>
              <h3>Example 1 – Web layout width</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose your content area is <strong>1200 px</strong> wide and
                you want a golden split between main content and sidebar.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total \(L = 1200\) px.</li>
                <li>
                  Longer segment \(a \approx 0.618 \times 1200 = 741.6\) px.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Shorter segment \(b \approx 0.382 \times 1200 = 458.4\) px.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                You might round to <strong>742 px</strong> main content and
                <strong>458 px</strong> sidebar.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 2 – Golden rectangle from height</h3>
              <p>
                You want a poster with height <strong>70 cm</strong> in golden
                ratio.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Given height \(h = 70\) cm.</li>
                <li>
                  Width \(w = \varphi \, h \approx 1.618 \times 70 \approx
                  113.26\) cm.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                So a golden rectangle poster would be about
                <strong>113 × 70 cm</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>Example 3 – Is my photo crop golden?</h3>
              <p>
                Your image is <strong>1920 × 1080 px</strong>. Check the ratio:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>\(a = 1920\), \(b = 1080\)</li>
                <li>\(a / b = 1920 / 1080 \approx 1.7778\)</li>
                <li>
                  Difference from φ ≈ \(|1.7778 - 1.6180| / 1.6180 \approx
                  9.9\%\)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                So 16:9 is <strong>not</strong> particularly close to the golden
                ratio.
              </p>

              <h2>Golden ratio in math, nature, and design</h2>
              <h3>1. Fibonacci numbers and φ</h3>
              <p>
                The golden ratio is closely related to the
                <strong>Fibonacci sequence</strong> (1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, …).
                The ratio of consecutive Fibonacci numbers approaches φ:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \frac{F_{n+1}}{F_n} \to \varphi \quad \text{as } n \to
                  \infty \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                This connection explains why φ appears in spirals and growth
                patterns that can be approximated by Fibonacci-like
                progressions.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Golden ratio in nature</h3>
              <p>
                Many natural patterns can be <em>approximated</em> by
                golden-ratio-related spirals or proportions, such as:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>phyllotaxis (arrangement of leaves and seeds)</li>
                <li>some flower petal counts (often Fibonacci numbers)</li>
                <li>
                  spiral shells and hurricanes (logarithmic spirals close to
                  φ-based growth)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                These are not perfect golden ratios, but φ often provides a
                useful mathematical model.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Golden ratio in art, architecture, and UX</h3>
              <p>Historically, the golden ratio has been associated with:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>classical architecture and Renaissance paintings</li>
                <li>book page layouts and typographic grids</li>
                <li>logo design and icon proportions</li>
                <li>
                  modern UI/UX layouts (e.g., content vs. sidebar, hero vs.
                  body)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                While some historical claims are exaggerated, φ remains a
                practical guideline for creating balanced compositions.
              </p>

              <h2>Practical tips for designers</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Start with content:</strong> Use φ to refine spacing
                  and hierarchy, not to force content into awkward shapes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Combine with other systems:</strong> Golden ratio
                  works well alongside grids, 8‑pt spacing, and rule-of-thirds.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use ranges, not absolutes:</strong> Being within a few
                  percent of φ is usually visually indistinguishable from exact
                  φ.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Test with users:</strong> A mathematically “perfect”
                  layout can still fail usability tests—prioritize clarity and
                  accessibility.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>What is the golden ratio?</h3>
              <p>
                The golden ratio is the number \(\varphi \approx 1.618\) that
                describes a special proportional relationship: the whole is to
                the larger part as the larger part is to the smaller part.
              </p>

              <h3>What is the exact formula for φ?</h3>
              <p>
                φ is the positive solution of the quadratic equation \(\varphi^2
                - \varphi - 1 = 0\), so:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\[ \varphi = \frac{1 + \sqrt{5}}{2} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h3>How accurate do I need to be?</h3>
              <p>
                For visual design, being within <strong>1–2%</strong> of φ is
                usually more than enough. Our ratio checker shows the percentage
                difference so you can judge how close you are.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use any units?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The golden ratio is <strong>dimensionless</strong>, so you
                can use pixels, centimeters, inches, points, or any other unit.
                Just be consistent within a calculation.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Is the golden ratio scientifically “proven” to be most
                beautiful?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Not universally. Some studies find preferences for φ-like
                proportions in specific contexts, but results are mixed. The
                golden ratio is best treated as a
                <strong>useful design heuristic</strong>, not a universal law of
                beauty.
              </p>
